<DOC><DOCNO> AP880706-0012 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 2357EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Germany-AIDSGloves     07-06 0143</FIRST><SECOND>PM-BRF--Germany-AIDS Gloves,0146</SECOND><HEAD>New Law Requires Motorists To Add `AIDS Gloves' To First Aid Kits</HEAD><DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Motorists in West Germany must add twopairs of surgical gloves to the first aid kits they are required tocarry in their automobiles under a new law designed to prevent thespread of AIDS.   Transportation Ministry spokesman Bernd Bialleck said Wednesdaythat the regulation takes effect October 1.   He said it aims to halt the spread of disease, especially AIDS,in situations where motorists give first aid to bleeding trafficaccident victims.   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome destroys the body's abilityto fight disease. It is fatal and a cure has not been found.   The virus is spread most often through sexual contact, needlesor syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or bloodproducts, and from pregnant women to their offspring.</TEXT></DOC>